insert into excerpts (id, book_id, "order", text) values
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000001',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000001',
   1,
   $$The cabin smelled of cedar and old smoke, and Eden hated the way Holt filled the doorway behind her, his shoulders blocking what little light the storm had left them. "There has to be another room," she said, not turning around. She knew there wasn't. She had checked the booking three times on the drive up, watching the snow swallow the road in her side mirror, watching the roof of his rental car disappear and reappear like something she could not get rid of. "There isn't," he said. He set his bag down with a thud, deliberate, the way he set down a quote in a column when he wanted her to feel it land. "You can have the bed." "I don't want your charity, Ravensdale." "It isn't charity, Pierce. It's geometry. You're five-foot-three. The couch is five-foot-two." She turned then, slowly, and found him already looking at her, and what she saw in his face was not the smug certainty she had been bracing for. He looked tired. He looked like a man who had driven six hours through a blizzard to reach a story neither of them wanted, and who had just realized that the worst part of the assignment was not the weather. "Fine," she said. "But the bedroom door locks." "I noticed." "Good." "Eden." His voice softened a degree she had not given him permission to use. "It's going to be a long night." Outside, the wind found a loose board on the porch and began, patiently, to take it apart.$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000002',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000001',
   2,
   $$The power gave out at 11:47. She knew the time because she had been staring at the microwave clock from her side of the kitchen, counting the seconds between the gusts, pretending she was not also counting the seconds between his breaths from the couch. Then the green numbers vanished and the cabin became a shape made of darker shapes, and Holt said, very quietly, "Don't move." "I wasn't going to." "You were. You always move when you're afraid." She heard him stand. She heard him cross the room with the unhurried care of a man who had learned where the furniture was without being asked to. A match flared. Then a second. Then the small, miraculous bloom of a hurricane lamp on the table between them, and his face above it, and the way the light caught the scar on his jaw she had pretended for three years she had never noticed. "Come here," he said. "It's warmer by the stove." She did not want to. She went anyway. She sat on the floor beside him with the blanket from the bedroom around her shoulders, and after a long time she said, "I am not afraid of the dark, Holt." "I know," he said. "That isn't what I meant." The wind hit the window like an open hand. He did not move closer. Neither did she. Somewhere between them, in the small bright space the lamp had made, something agreed to wait.$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000003',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000001',
   3,
   $$She woke to the smell of coffee and the impossible quiet of a world buried under three feet of new snow. For a moment she did not remember where she was. Then she remembered everything. The blanket on her shoulders was not the one she had fallen asleep under. It was his. It smelled like him in a way that felt like an accusation. She found him in the kitchen, sleeves rolled, hair still damp from whatever cold-water arrangement he had made with the bathroom tap, and he did not look up when she came in. He poured a second mug. He set it on the counter at the exact distance from his own that meant she could choose. "You snore," he said. "I don't." "You do. Quietly. Like an argument." She wrapped her hands around the mug and felt the heat go through her like a confession. "Holt." "Don't." "Don't what?" He finally looked at her, and the storm had done something to his eyes that the storm had no right to do. "Don't say something now that you'll have to take back when the road clears." The kettle ticked. The fire in the stove shifted and resettled. Outside the window, the world was so white it looked like a page someone had not yet written on. "I won't take it back," she said. He set down his mug. He did not come closer. He just looked at her like a man who was, finally, listening.$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000004',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000002',
   1,
   $$Theo could always tell which boyfriend it was by the way Margot closed the front door. The accountant had been a soft, embarrassed click. The bartender had been a deliberate, slightly drunken push. The one she had been seeing for the last four months, the one Theo had not allowed himself to learn the name of, closed doors like he was trying not to be heard, which was its own kind of loud. Tonight the door did not close at all for a long moment. Then it closed the way doors close when the person on the other side has just stopped pretending. He knew, before he heard her bedroom door, before he heard the bed take her weight, that this one was over. He turned the page of his book without reading it. Their walls had been a joke since the day they signed the lease. "Pre-war character," the listing had said, which apparently meant any conversation conducted at a normal volume could be heard from the next apartment as if through a phone with a bad connection. They had laughed about it. They had agreed on signals. Three knocks meant put your headphones on. Two knocks meant I know, and I'm sorry, and I'm here. He had never used the second one. He used it now. The silence on the other side of the wall went very still. Then, after a moment that felt much longer than a moment, he heard two soft knocks back. He closed his book. He did not move from his side of the wall. He just sat there, listening to her not cry, and let her not be alone.$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000005',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000002',
   2,
   $$It was 2:14 in the morning when she finally said his name through the wall. "Theo." She said it the way you say a word you have been holding in your mouth for years and have only now decided to taste. "I'm here." "I have to tell you something, and I cannot tell it to your face. I need the wall." He set his palm against the plaster, an old habit, the same way she had set her palm against it the night her father died. "Okay." "I think I have been in love with you since the radiator broke in February of our second year. You came home with two space heaters and a bag of oranges and you said the oranges were because heat costs sugar, which is the stupidest thing anyone has ever said to me, and I have never recovered." The wall was cool against his hand. He could feel, or imagined he could feel, the answering pressure of her palm on the other side, half an inch and one impossible decision away. "Margot." "Don't say it kindly. Don't say it like a friend. If you have to say no, say it like you mean it, because I will not survive a kind no." He closed his eyes. He thought about the oranges. He thought about every cup of coffee he had ever made her, and the way she fell asleep on his couch during movies she had picked, and the small specific sound she made when she was about to laugh and was trying not to. "Open your door," he said. "Theo." "Margot. Open your door."$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000006',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000003',
   1,
   $$The bell over the door had not been replaced. That was the first thing she noticed, and it almost broke her. It was the same brass bell with the same slightly cracked tone, and it announced her into the same long room with the same uneven floorboards, and for a moment Wren stood in the doorway of the Cedar Hollow Coffee Co. and forgot that eight years had passed at all. Then he looked up from the espresso machine. Sawyer's hands did not stop moving. That was what she would remember, later, when she tried to tell the story to herself in a way that did not hurt. He kept tamping the shot, kept wiping the portafilter, kept doing the small precise work of his life, while his eyes did the larger work of recognizing her and choosing, in real time, not to drop anything. "Hi," she said. The word came out smaller than she had practiced. "Hi." He pulled the shot. He set the cup down. He did not smile, but he did not look away either, which was worse, because looking away would have been a thing she could have answered. "I didn't know if you'd still be here." "Where else would I be." It was not a question. It was the answer to a question she had failed to ask eight years ago, and they both knew it, and the knowing of it sat between them on the counter like a third cup nobody had ordered. "Sawyer." "What can I get you, Wren." His voice did not break. Hers almost did. "A long time," she said. "Please. If you have one."$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000007',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000003',
   2,
   $$He let her stay until closing. He did not invite her to. He just did not ask her to leave when he flipped the sign at nine, and she took that for what it was, which was the first generous thing he had given her since she walked back into his life that morning. She helped him stack the chairs because she remembered how. She wiped down the espresso bar because she remembered that too, the angle of the cloth, the way the steam wand had to be purged twice or the milk would taste of the afternoon. When everything was clean and the lights above the counter had been turned down to the low amber that used to be her favorite hour of any day, Sawyer leaned against the back counter and looked at her like a man who had been rehearsing one sentence for eight years. "You didn't even leave a note." "I know." "Wren. You didn't leave a note." "I know." Her hands found the edge of the bar and held on. "I thought a note would make it real. I thought if I didn't write anything down, I could come back before you noticed I was gone. And then a week became a month became a job became a life, and every day I didn't come back was another day I couldn't come back." "Until today." "Until today." He was quiet for a long time. The fridge hummed. A car passed on Cedar Street and was gone. "I noticed," he said, finally. "I noticed every day." She did not trust herself to speak. He pushed off the counter, walked the length of the bar that had stood between them all night, and stopped on her side of it. "Why today, Wren." "Because I finally had something to put in the note," she said.$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000008',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000004',
   1,
   $$"Five rules," Imogen said, sliding the napkin across the table. She had written them on the back of a Pret receipt during her lunch hour and she was not, under any circumstances, going to admit how long it had taken her. Daniel did not pick up the napkin. He just looked at it the way he looked at opposing counsel's exhibits, with the unhurried suspicion of a man who had already decided what he thought. "Number one," he read aloud. "No physical contact in the office." "Obviously." "Number two. No personal questions outside the cover story." "Cover story being what, exactly." "That we met at my sister's birthday in March, that you make me laugh, and that I am bringing you to the gala because the alternative is bringing my mother." "Plausible." "Number three. No alcohol past two glasses." "For me, or for both of us." "For both of us. I have seen you after three." His mouth almost moved. Not quite. "Number four. The arrangement ends Sunday at midnight." "And number five." She had been hoping he would let her keep that one folded under his thumb. He turned the napkin over instead, slowly, the way he turned over the last page of a contract before signing it. "No falling for each other." "It's a formality." "Is it." "Cho." "Vale." The waiter arrived with their coffees, set them down, sensed the air pressure in the booth, and left without offering cream. Daniel folded the napkin, very precisely, and put it in his inside pocket. "I'll need a copy," he said, "in case of dispute."$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000009',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000004',
   2,
   $$She had not expected him to wear the cufflinks. She had given them to him as a joke at the office Secret Santa two years ago, when she had been the kind of person who could buy Daniel Cho a pair of small silver scales and call it a comment on his personality. He was wearing them now, at the wrist of a tuxedo she had not been prepared for, under the chandelier of a ballroom she had been to a dozen times and had never seen properly until tonight. "You look," he said, and then stopped, because he was not the sort of man who finished that sentence in public. "I know," she said, which was not a thing she would have said to anyone else, and which was, technically, a violation of nothing on the napkin. He offered his arm. She took it. They walked into the room the way people walk into rooms they have decided to be brave in, and three of the senior partners looked up at once, and Imogen felt his hand settle, very lightly, against the small of her back. It was, by the strictest reading, allowed. They were no longer in the office. "Rule one," she murmured. "Office," he murmured back. "Not ballroom." "How convenient." "How accidental." Across the room, a string quartet began something slow and unhurried, and Daniel, who did not dance, who had told her at length last Tuesday that he did not dance, turned to her with the polite formality of a man requesting a favor from opposing counsel and said, "Vale. May I." She looked up at him. The cufflinks caught the light. "On the record, Cho?" "Off," he said. "Entirely off."$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000010',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000004',
   3,
   $$The cab smelled of rain and somebody else's perfume and the long, late hour of a night that was supposed to have ended already. He had given the driver her address first. That was the small thing she was going to think about, later, when she tried to figure out exactly when the napkin had stopped mattering. He had given the driver her address first, which meant he had decided, somewhere between the third dance and the cloakroom, that he would be the one who went home alone tonight. "Daniel." "Mm." His head was back against the seat. His eyes were closed. His hand was on the seat between them, palm up, in the universal posture of a man who was not going to ask. "Rule five." He did not open his eyes. "What about it." "I think we should renegotiate." There was a long pause, the kind of pause that, in a deposition, would have made her very nervous. Then he turned his head, slowly, and looked at her in the half-dark of the back seat with an expression she had never seen on him in any conference room. "Vale," he said, very quietly. "If we renegotiate rule five, the entire contract is void." "I know." "Counsel," he said, and the word had become something else entirely, "is that what you want." The cab turned onto her street. The driver, with the patient cynicism of every cab driver in this city, slowed without being asked. "Yes," Imogen said. He took her hand. He did not say anything else. He did not need to. The contract, very quietly, fell apart between them like a paper boat in the rain.$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000011',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000005',
   1,
   $$He arrived on a Tuesday with a thermos of tea, a tote bag full of what looked like every philosophy book ever assigned to an undergraduate, and a smile Marlow was not equipped to handle before her second coffee. "You must be Ms. Quinn," he said. "I'm Jude. From the ad?" "There was no ad." "There was a card. In the window. It said 'Help Wanted, inquire within, no cheerful people.'" "And you walked in anyway." "I thought it was a joke." "It wasn't." He set the thermos down on the counter, very carefully, as if he had been raised to respect other people's surfaces, and looked around the shop with the slow appreciative attention of someone who actually knew what he was looking at. The light through the front window picked out the gold on the spines of the Folio editions she had been meaning to dust for a month. He saw the dust. He did not say anything about the dust. "I can't pay much," she said. "I figured." "And I am not, by any clinical definition, a pleasant person to work with." "I figured that too." "Then why are you here." He considered her. He had the kind of face that considered things rather than reacted to them, which was already, against her will, narrowing one of her objections to him. "Because I read your interview in the Quill Street Quarterly," he said, "and you said the only thing more dangerous than a bad book was a person who hadn't been ruined by a good one. And I want to learn how to talk about books like that. I don't think they teach it at school." Marlow looked at him for a long moment. Then she pushed the spare apron across the counter and said, "You start now. The poetry section is a war crime."$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000012',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000005',
   2,
   $$It was past midnight by the time they finished shelving the last of the new arrivals, and Marlow could not remember the last time the shop had been this clean. She also could not remember the last time she had stayed past closing because she wanted to. Jude was on the floor with his back against the philosophy section, sleeves rolled, hair in his eyes, reading something out of a battered copy of Rilke as if she had asked him to. She had not asked him to. He had just started, somewhere around the third hour, the way a person starts humming when they think no one is listening. "You're not going to convert me," she said, from the counter. "I am not trying to." "You are absolutely trying to." "I am trying to find one good line. There's a difference." "And if you find it." He looked up at her over the top of the book. The shop was the small warm yellow of the desk lamp and the long blue of the night through the front window, and his face was caught between them in a way she did not have a word for. "Then I read it to you," he said, "and we both go home." She came around the counter without deciding to. She sat down on the floor across from him, close enough to see the page, far enough to keep the rule she had not yet broken about touching the new employee, and said, "Read it now." "I haven't found it yet." "Then read until you do." He read. The clock above the door clicked over to one. She did not move. Somewhere in the third poem she stopped pretending she was listening for the line, and started listening for the way his voice slowed when he was about to underline something. He found the line at 1:17. He read it twice. The second time, she was already looking at him.$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000013',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000006',
   1,
   $$"What do you mean, one room." Cassidy was using the voice she used in budget meetings, which was the voice she used when she was not yet panicking but wanted to be on the record as having had standing to panic later. The desk clerk, a teenager whose name tag said HENRY and whose face said NOT MY FAULT, slid the reservation printout across the counter. "The booking under Riverton Holdings was for one room, ma'am. The other room got cancelled in the system this morning. The storm took out the line; we couldn't reach anyone." "And there is nothing else." "There is nothing else in this building, on this island, or on the next island, ma'am. The ferry isn't running until Wednesday." Behind her, Owen had gone very still. She did not have to turn around to know it. She had spent four years sitting two desks away from him in an open-plan office, and she could read the precise quality of his stillness the way other people read body language. This was the stillness of a man calculating exactly how much of a problem this was for him personally. He had a reason to be calculating. They both did. "We'll take it," he said. "Owen." "Cass. We'll take it." "There is one bed." "I noticed." "There are people from the Toronto office in the dining room downstairs." "I know." "There is a member of the board of directors," she said, lowering her voice, "sitting at the bar." His hand found the small of her back, light and brief, the way it had found her back at the airport when they had been pretending not to know each other. He took the room key from Henry. "Then we will be very quiet," he said.$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000014',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000006',
   2,
   $$The bed was made of iron and made noise. That was the first discovery. The second was that the inn had been built in 1894 and that the floorboards beneath the rug had been tuned, by a century of lonely guests, to a specific frequency of betrayal. They both stood inside the door for a long moment after he locked it, looking at the bed the way people look at evidence. "I will sleep on the floor," Owen said. "You will not sleep on the floor. The floor is the floor of an 1894 inn. The floor will give you tetanus." "Then you sleep on the floor." "Owen." She set down her bag. She turned the deadbolt herself, because she did not entirely trust the deadbolt he had just turned. "We have shared worse spaces than this. We shared the supply closet during the fire alarm in 2022." "We did not share the supply closet," he said, very quietly. "We hid in the supply closet. There is a difference." "Is there." The room was small and warm and smelled faintly of cedar, and outside the single window the snow was coming down again in the slow, conspiratorial way it had been coming down all day, and Cassidy realized, with the kind of clarity that arrives only when there is nowhere left to escape to, that she had been waiting for this room for four years. He was looking at her the way he had been not looking at her since the Toronto trip. "Cass." "Don't say anything yet." "I have to. Once we're in this room, if we say it, we cannot un-say it. If anyone downstairs ever finds out" "I know what they would do. I have known what they would do every day for four years." "And." "And I am tired," she said, "of letting people who do not love us decide what we get to have."$$),
  ('22222222-2222-2222-2222-000000000015',
   '11111111-1111-1111-1111-000000000006',
   3,
   $$She woke before he did. The room was still the dim blue of the hour before sunrise, and the storm had finally, finally, exhausted itself against the side of the inn. Owen was asleep on his back with one arm flung across the pillow she had been using, and his hand was open the way his hands were never open in meetings, and Cassidy, looking at him in the gray light of a morning neither of them knew how to walk into, understood that there was not going to be a clean way out of this. There was going to be a board meeting on Tuesday. There was going to be a Slack message from HR. There was going to be a whole architecture of consequences that the two of them had built between themselves, brick by careful brick, over the course of four years of pretending. And none of those consequences had been here in the room with them last night. She thought about waking him. She thought about not. She thought about how, in every story she had ever read about a morning like this one, the woman either left a note and disappeared or stayed and made coffee, and how both of those choices were a kind of answer to a question she had not yet decided to ask. She did not leave. She did not make coffee. She lay back down on her side, very carefully, so that the iron bed would not give them away to the floor below, and she put her hand inside his open one, and she watched the gray light find the corners of the room. He woke up that way. He did not move his hand. "Cass," he said, and his voice was the voice of a man who had been awake longer than he was admitting. "I'm still here," she said. "I noticed," he said. The inn was very quiet. Downstairs, no one had any idea.$$)
on conflict (id) do nothing;
